Rest, Hydration and Medication.
Fever is a natural response of the body to an infection or inflammation, caused by an immune reaction that increases body temperature above normal levels. Most fevers can be treated with self-care measures at home and do not require medical attention unless they are extremely high or last for more than 3 days.
Rest and hydration are crucial to help the body recover from a fever, as the immune system needs rest to fight off the infection. Drinking plenty of fluids such as water, clear broths, or electrolyte-rich beverages like coconut water can help replace lost fluids and electrolytes and prevent dehydration.
In some cases, medication may be prescribed to reduce fever in adults and children over 3 months old. Acetaminophen (Tylenol) or ibuprofen (Advil, Motrin) are commonly used to treat mild to moderate fevers. Always follow the recommended dosage instructions on the label and consult with a healthcare provider before giving medication to children.

exercise. everybody knows that exercise is good for your body, but it turns out that it's also great for relieving back pain.
When you exercise regularly, it helps to strengthen the muscles in your back, which can help to support and protect the spine. This can be especially helpful if you have a herniated disc or other injury that is causing your back pain.
Additionally, exercise can help to improve your flexibility and range of motion, which can make it easier to move around and perform daily activities without feeling limited by your back pain.
It's important to note that different types of exercise may be more effective for different types of back pain. For example, yoga and Pilates are great for strengthening the core muscles that support the spine, while aerobic exercises like running or cycling can help to improve circulation and reduce inflammation.
Overall, incorporating regular exercise into your routine is one of the best ways to naturally relieve back pain without relying on medication or other treatments.
